{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567403"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:01:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:01:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18971"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18971"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.06,0.7,0.11,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11705"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80618"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11705","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11705"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18971"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65910"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1157"},{"type":"tags","id":"4029"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"5788"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27546"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43715"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80618"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 77-year-old woman is admitted to the palliative care ward for symptom management of metastatic ovarian cancer. She takes modified-release morphine 30 mg twice daily with immediate-release morphine 10 mg tablets for breakthrough pain. She has no other significant medical history and takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears comfortable at rest. Her vital signs are within normal limits. She is lucid and coherent when interviewed. Her family reports that while her background pain control is good, she becomes profoundly drowsy for several hours after taking breakthrough doses.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Change to alternative opioid","Add naloxone","Reduce immediate-release morphine dose","Reduce modified-release morphine dose","Cease immediate-release morphine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms of opioid toxicity (drowsiness) specifically related to breakthrough doses, while maintaining good pain control on her background modified-release morphine. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReducing the immediate-release morphine dose\u003C/strong\u003E is most appropriate. A typical breakthrough dose is 1/6th to 1/10th of the total daily background opioid dose. In this case, the total daily background dose is 60 mg, suggesting the 10 mg breakthrough dose may be too high. Reducing it to 5-6 mg would be reasonable while maintaining the same background dose.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReducing the modified-release morphine dose\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as the background pain control is good and there are no side effects from the regular doses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanging to alternative opioid\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary when the issue can be addressed by simple dose adjustment. Opioid rotation would be considered if side effects persisted despite dose adjustment or if pain control was inadequate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdding naloxone\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this would reverse all opioid effects including pain control. Naloxone is reserved for severe opioid toxicity with respiratory depression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECeasing immediate-release morphine\u003C/strong\u003E entirely would leave the patient without options for breakthrough pain management, which is an essential component of good palliative care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle is to maintain effective background analgesia while adjusting breakthrough doses to achieve optimal pain control without unacceptable side effects. Regular review and adjustment of both background and breakthrough doses is essential in palliative care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opioid toxicity should be suspected when patients develop drowsiness after breakthrough doses despite stable background analgesia","Reducing the breakthrough dose while maintaining background analgesia is appropriate when side effects occur from breakthrough doses","Regular review of both background and breakthrough opioid doses is essential in palliative care to optimise symptom control"],"references":["Zimmerman A, Laitman A. Safe Management of Adverse Effects Associated with Prescription Opioids in the Palliative Care Population: A Narrative Review. Journal of Clinical Medicine. 2024; 13(10):2746. https://doi.org/10.3390/jcm13102746. Available online at ; https://www.mdpi.com/2077-0383/13/10/2746","Pickard J, McDonald E, Hindmarsh J. Opioid use in palliative care: Selection, initiation and optimisation. Pharm. J. 2020;10. Available online at ; https://pharmaceutical-journal.com/article/ld/opioid-use-in-palliative-care-selection-initiation-and-optimisation"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65910"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18971"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65910"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T21:15:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T21:17:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":